Session 2

Import the fpp library

library(fpp)

library(tseries)

library(ggplot2)

library(forecast)

Example I - Regression Example

tslm() -

Fit a linear model with time series components tslm is used to fit linear models to time series including trend and seasonality components See ?tslm

usconsumption dataset

Growth rates of personal consumption and personal income in the USA.

Description: Percentage changes in quarterly personal consumption expenditure and personal disposable income for the US, 1970 to 2010.

See ?usconsumption for additional information

Plot data

plot(usconsumption, ylab="% change in consumption and income",
     plot.type="single", col=1:2, xlab="Year")
legend("topright", legend=c("Consumption","Income"),
       lty=1, col=c(1,2), cex=.9)

plot(consumption ~ income, data=usconsumption,
     ylab="% change in consumption", xlab="% change in income")

Fit linear timeseries model

fit <- tslm(consumption ~ income, data=usconsumption)
summary(fit)
## 
## Call:
## tslm(formula = consumption ~ income, data = usconsumption)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.3681 -0.3237  0.0266  0.3436  1.5581 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  0.52062    0.06231   8.356 2.79e-14 ***
## income       0.31866    0.05226   6.098 7.61e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.6274 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1867, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1817 
## F-statistic: 37.18 on 1 and 162 DF,  p-value: 7.614e-09
plot(consumption ~ income, data=usconsumption,
     ylab="% change in consumption", xlab="% change in income")
abline(fit)

Forecast consumption

Forecast consumption if there is a 2% growth in income for each of the quarters in 2011. Alternatively a 3% decline in income for each of the quarters may be of interest.

fcast <- forecast(fit, newdata=data.frame(income=c(-3,2)))


plot(fcast, ylab="% change in consumption", xlab="% change in income")

res <- ts(resid(fit),s=1970.25,f=4)


plot.ts(res,ylab="res (Consumption)")
abline(0,0)

Check Residuals

checkresiduals(fit)

## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 8
## 
## data:  Residuals from Linear regression model
## LM test = 24.182, df = 8, p-value = 0.002136
# p-value  < 0.05 ==> Accept Alternative hypothesis ==> Residuals are autocorrelated

Example II - Classical Decomposition

decompose function

Classical Seasonal Decomposition by Moving Averages

Description: Decompose a time series into seasonal, trend and irregular components using moving averages. Deals with additive or multiplicative seasonal component.

See ?decompose for additional information

Exponential smoothing forecasts Functions

Level

ses(y, h = 10, level = c(80, 95), fan = FALSE, initial = c(“optimal”, “simple”), alpha = NULL, lambda = NULL, biasadj = FALSE, x = y, …)

Level + Trend

holt(y, h = 10, damped = FALSE, level = c(80, 95), fan = FALSE, initial = c(“optimal”, “simple”), exponential = FALSE, alpha = NULL, beta = NULL, phi = NULL, lambda = NULL, biasadj = FALSE, x = y, …)

Level + Trend + Seasonality

hw(y, h = 2 * frequency(x), seasonal = c(“additive”, “multiplicative”), damped = FALSE, level = c(80, 95), fan = FALSE, initial = c(“optimal”, “simple”), exponential = FALSE, alpha = NULL, beta = NULL, gamma = NULL, phi = NULL, lambda = NULL, biasadj = FALSE, x = y, …)

austourists Dataset

data<-austourists

International Tourists to Australia: Total visitor nights. Description: Quarterly visitor nights spent by international tourists to Australia. 1999-2010

See ?austourists for additional information

Load and plot data

data<-austourists 

plot(data)

decompose

fit_add <- decompose(data, type="additive")

plot(fit_add)

fit_mult <- decompose(data, type="multiplicative")

plot(fit_mult)

Fit Exponential smoothing forecasts

fit_hw <- hw(data, h=24, seasonal="mult",
           damped=TRUE)
summary(fit_hw)

Example III - Seasonal Holt Winter

co2 Dataset

Mauna Loa Atmospheric CO2 Concentration Description: Atmospheric concentrations of CO2 are expressed in parts per million (ppm) and reported in the preliminary 1997 SIO manometric mole fraction scale.

Plot data

data<-co2 # Mauna Loa Atmospheric CO2 Concentration
plot(data)

m_add <- hw(data,seasonal = "additive",h=48) # or ?HoltWinters
m_multi <- hw(data,seasonal = "multiplicative",h=48) # or ?HoltWinters
m_Damped_add <- hw(data,seasonal = "additive",h=48, damped = TRUE) # or ?HoltWinters
par(mfrow=c(3,1), fig=c(0,1,0,1))
plot(m_add)

plot(m_multi)

plot(m_Damped_add)
